1
00:00:06,371 --> 00:00:08,640
[♪]

2
00:01:04,153 --> 00:01:06,388
CREW MAN:
There it is, Astro.

3
00:01:06,421 --> 00:01:07,756
The Space Academy.

4
00:01:07,789 --> 00:01:10,191
ASTRO:
Wow! It's even bigger
than I thought.

5
00:01:10,224 --> 00:01:10,891
CREW MAN:
That's right.

6
00:01:10,924 --> 00:01:12,292
And no better place for training

7
00:01:12,326 --> 00:01:14,227
future astronauts
and rocket scientists.

8
00:01:14,261 --> 00:01:16,329
ASTRO:
This is gonna be awesome.

9
00:01:16,363 --> 00:01:17,764
I'll bet everyone here
has a blast.

10
00:01:17,797 --> 00:01:20,099
[EXPLOSION]

11
00:01:20,132 --> 00:01:23,234
[ALL YELLING]

12
00:01:30,174 --> 00:01:31,608
[ALL YELLING]

13
00:01:32,809 --> 00:01:33,777
Hmm? What?

14
00:01:37,513 --> 00:01:39,415
What on earth
is going on here?

15
00:01:39,448 --> 00:01:42,450
Uh, other than
the raging fireball,

16
00:01:42,484 --> 00:01:44,219
not much, sir!

17
00:01:44,252 --> 00:01:46,888
Huh? What in the...?

18
00:01:46,921 --> 00:01:49,223
Oh!

19
00:01:50,357 --> 00:01:52,192
Whoa! Argh!

20
00:01:54,227 --> 00:01:55,428
Huh?

21
00:01:55,461 --> 00:01:56,629
Grr!

22
00:01:56,662 --> 00:01:58,631
[NERVOUSLY]
Yaah... Sorry!

23
00:01:58,664 --> 00:02:01,300
Anton! Not again!
What have you gone and done?

24
00:02:01,333 --> 00:02:02,367
Oh!

25
00:02:02,401 --> 00:02:03,435
And
Dr. O'Shay--

26
00:02:03,468 --> 00:02:05,236
ALL:
Whoa!

27
00:02:05,269 --> 00:02:06,870
Gangway! Mad fireball!

28
00:02:06,904 --> 00:02:08,739
Huh?

29
00:02:10,407 --> 00:02:11,441
Gotta fly!

30
00:02:11,474 --> 00:02:13,343
Hey!

31
00:02:13,376 --> 00:02:14,377
[GASPS]

32
00:02:16,245 --> 00:02:18,247
Ugh! No!

33
00:02:18,280 --> 00:02:19,915
Whoa!

34
00:02:19,948 --> 00:02:21,683
[GRUNTING]

35
00:02:28,655 --> 00:02:29,689
Huh?

36
00:02:35,328 --> 00:02:36,895
ASTRO:
Huh?

37
00:02:45,369 --> 00:02:47,838
Oh!

38
00:02:47,871 --> 00:02:49,606
WOMAN:
Are you all right?

39
00:02:49,640 --> 00:02:51,907
Yeah. Thanks.

40
00:02:51,941 --> 00:02:53,309
Good.

41
00:02:53,343 --> 00:02:55,277
That was a close one.

42
00:02:55,310 --> 00:02:58,780
Was it ever!
That was an amazing save.

43
00:02:58,813 --> 00:03:01,249
You just grabbed
that thing in midair

44
00:03:01,282 --> 00:03:03,351
and yanked out exactly the right
wire to keep it from--

45
00:03:03,384 --> 00:03:05,185
[STUTTERING]

46
00:03:10,890 --> 00:03:13,792
You must be Astro.
My name is--

47
00:03:13,825 --> 00:03:14,626
ANTON:
Briana!

48
00:03:14,660 --> 00:03:16,362
Hi, Anton.

49
00:03:16,395 --> 00:03:17,462
Much better.

50
00:03:17,496 --> 00:03:20,631
Your latest invention
only wiped out half the school.

51
00:03:20,665 --> 00:03:22,800
Whoa!

52
00:03:22,833 --> 00:03:25,869
Hi. I'm Astro.

53
00:03:25,902 --> 00:03:27,237
This is a CO2 engine, right?

54
00:03:27,271 --> 00:03:28,304
Yep.

55
00:03:28,337 --> 00:03:29,572
Great design!
Thanks.

56
00:03:29,605 --> 00:03:32,341
You'd better invent
a disappearing machine

57
00:03:32,375 --> 00:03:33,942
before the headmaster
finds you.

58
00:03:33,976 --> 00:03:37,945
This is the third time you've
nearly destroyed the place.

59
00:03:37,979 --> 00:03:39,414
Good thing you didn't
dent the <i>Falcon.</i>

60
00:03:39,447 --> 00:03:40,715
ANTON:
That's for sure.

61
00:03:40,748 --> 00:03:43,517
So that's the <i>Falcon Two!</i>

62
00:03:43,550 --> 00:03:44,685
You know it?

63
00:03:44,718 --> 00:03:46,787
The new
experimental starship.

64
00:03:46,820 --> 00:03:49,355
I'm supposed to help
design its guidance system.

65
00:03:49,389 --> 00:03:50,523
BOTH:
You!
That's right.

66
00:03:50,556 --> 00:03:52,557
Oh.

67
00:03:54,493 --> 00:03:56,227
Then we'll be
working together.

68
00:03:56,260 --> 00:03:57,295
Huh?

69
00:03:57,328 --> 00:03:58,662
Uh, you and me?

70
00:03:58,696 --> 00:03:59,530
Whoa! Whoa!

71
00:03:59,563 --> 00:04:00,831
Oh!

72
00:04:00,864 --> 00:04:03,633
Uh, I gotta go
and do a, uh, thing.

73
00:04:03,667 --> 00:04:04,734
Whoa!

74
00:04:04,767 --> 00:04:05,702
Uh, I gotta go!

75
00:04:05,735 --> 00:04:06,803
Bye!

76
00:04:06,836 --> 00:04:07,937
Whoa!

77
00:04:07,970 --> 00:04:10,372
Whoa! Whoa!

78
00:04:10,406 --> 00:04:11,840
Bye!

79
00:04:11,873 --> 00:04:12,974
BOTH:
Huh?

80
00:04:17,712 --> 00:04:20,380
ASTRO:
This nervous feeling in my chest

81
00:04:20,414 --> 00:04:22,982
just won't go away.

82
00:04:23,016 --> 00:04:24,951
Internal temperature,
0.3 degrees higher than usual.

83
00:04:24,984 --> 00:04:25,885
Hey, what are you doing?

84
00:04:25,919 --> 00:04:26,953
Huh!

85
00:04:26,986 --> 00:04:29,688
Whoa!

86
00:04:30,823 --> 00:04:32,324
Cool circuits.

87
00:04:32,357 --> 00:04:33,558
Excuse me?

88
00:04:33,591 --> 00:04:35,360
Oh, sorry.
It's all right.

89
00:04:35,393 --> 00:04:37,428
So how come
you're here, Anton?

90
00:04:37,461 --> 00:04:38,996
Because I live here.

91
00:04:39,030 --> 00:04:42,599
This is my room,
and these are all my inventions.

92
00:04:42,633 --> 00:04:45,601
And you must be
my new roomie.

93
00:04:45,635 --> 00:04:46,702
Well, then,

94
00:04:46,736 --> 00:04:48,704
welcome to the Academy,
roomie.

95
00:04:48,738 --> 00:04:50,405
All right!

96
00:04:53,675 --> 00:04:55,509
ENGINEER:
So, Astro, what do you think of

97
00:04:55,543 --> 00:04:57,611
our blueprint for <i>Falcon Two?</i>

98
00:04:57,645 --> 00:04:58,912
ASTRO:
Hmm.

99
00:04:58,946 --> 00:05:01,581
My analysis detects
three excess circuit paths,

100
00:05:01,614 --> 00:05:04,316
which means 6 percent
of its power is wasted.

101
00:05:04,350 --> 00:05:06,752
We need to bring it down
to no more than 2 percent.

102
00:05:06,785 --> 00:05:09,488
Impossible. No one's ever
gotten it that low.

103
00:05:09,521 --> 00:05:10,756
ASTRO:
If we bypass the grid,

104
00:05:10,789 --> 00:05:11,890
we can get it
to zero.

105
00:05:11,923 --> 00:05:13,258
ALL:
Zero?

106
00:05:16,493 --> 00:05:17,561
Wha--

107
00:05:17,594 --> 00:05:18,695
Whoa!

108
00:05:18,728 --> 00:05:19,963
Uh...

109
00:05:19,996 --> 00:05:21,931
Excuse me. I left
the bathtub running. Oh!

110
00:05:26,802 --> 00:05:28,436
Ah!

111
00:05:30,772 --> 00:05:34,942
It's up another 0.7 degrees.
What is happening to me?

112
00:05:34,976 --> 00:05:36,843
Astro?
Huh?

113
00:05:36,877 --> 00:05:38,779
I've been
looking for you.

114
00:05:38,812 --> 00:05:40,780
That was truly amazing.

115
00:05:40,813 --> 00:05:42,014
Oh...

116
00:05:42,047 --> 00:05:44,449
Yes, a brilliant analysis.

117
00:05:44,483 --> 00:05:45,985
You're just what
the program needs.

118
00:05:46,018 --> 00:05:47,919
Say, do you smell
something burning?

119
00:05:47,952 --> 00:05:49,688
Anyway, with you here,

120
00:05:49,721 --> 00:05:53,391
I know we'll get <i>Falcon Two</i>
off the ground.

121
00:05:56,960 --> 00:06:00,963
ASTRO:
<i>Not a single</i>
<i>malfunctioning circuit.</i>

122
00:06:00,997 --> 00:06:04,066
<i>What is wrong with me?</i>

123
00:06:14,474 --> 00:06:15,675
[ANTON SIGHS]

124
00:06:15,709 --> 00:06:17,411
Huh?

125
00:06:18,745 --> 00:06:21,647
What's the matter,
Anton? Can't sleep?

126
00:06:21,680 --> 00:06:23,716
Astro, can I
tell you a secret?

127
00:06:23,749 --> 00:06:25,450
Um, sure.

128
00:06:25,483 --> 00:06:26,551
Well, the thing is--

129
00:06:26,584 --> 00:06:27,652
Yeah?

130
00:06:27,685 --> 00:06:29,987
Well...

131
00:06:30,021 --> 00:06:32,956
I'm crazy about Briana!

132
00:06:32,989 --> 00:06:34,491
Oh.

133
00:06:34,525 --> 00:06:36,359
But I'm just too chicken
to tell her.

134
00:06:36,392 --> 00:06:37,660
Would you
do it for me?

135
00:06:37,693 --> 00:06:39,028
Huh?

136
00:06:39,061 --> 00:06:42,497
I know, it's an awful
lot to ask,

137
00:06:42,531 --> 00:06:44,366
but every time
I try to tell her,

138
00:06:44,399 --> 00:06:45,734
my knees get
all wobbly.

139
00:06:45,767 --> 00:06:46,968
[WHIMPERS]

140
00:06:47,001 --> 00:06:48,636
You're the only one
who can help me.

141
00:06:48,669 --> 00:06:50,504
Why me?

142
00:06:50,538 --> 00:06:52,005
Because she respects you.

143
00:06:52,039 --> 00:06:54,041
You're working
with her every day.

144
00:06:54,074 --> 00:06:55,708
So maybe you could just
casually, you know,

145
00:06:55,742 --> 00:06:57,744
ask her if she likes me.

146
00:06:57,777 --> 00:07:00,979
I just-- I don't know
where else to turn, Astro.

147
00:07:01,012 --> 00:07:02,047
Will you?

148
00:07:02,080 --> 00:07:04,515
Uh, well, I--

149
00:07:04,549 --> 00:07:05,916
Please don't say no!

150
00:07:05,950 --> 00:07:07,652
I'm desperate. I really,
really like her a lot.

151
00:07:07,685 --> 00:07:09,620
Hmm.

152
00:07:17,460 --> 00:07:20,829
ASTRO:
<i>"Dear Briana..."</i>

153
00:07:20,863 --> 00:07:23,031
ASTRO:
Briana!

154
00:07:23,065 --> 00:07:25,800
Astro! What's up?

155
00:07:25,833 --> 00:07:27,969
I, uh-- Um...

156
00:07:28,002 --> 00:07:30,471
Do you have time to go with me
to the cafeteria?

157
00:07:30,504 --> 00:07:32,706
There are so many things
I want to ask about you.

158
00:07:32,739 --> 00:07:34,807
Me? Uh...

159
00:07:34,840 --> 00:07:36,141
Um, Anton--

160
00:07:36,175 --> 00:07:37,476
Anton?

161
00:07:37,509 --> 00:07:40,412
Yeah. Um, what do you
think of him?

162
00:07:40,445 --> 00:07:43,782
Well, I think he has
a lot of potential.

163
00:07:43,815 --> 00:07:46,950
He just needs to learn
to focus a little bit more.

164
00:07:46,984 --> 00:07:51,888
His head is usually
somewhere in the clouds.

165
00:07:51,921 --> 00:07:56,158
It's like he's always thinking
about something else.

166
00:07:56,192 --> 00:08:00,195
If I had his smarts,
there'd be no stopping me.

167
00:08:00,228 --> 00:08:03,564
The thing is, um, Anton asked me
to give you a letter.

168
00:08:03,598 --> 00:08:04,465
A letter?

169
00:08:07,234 --> 00:08:09,469
Hmm.

170
00:08:10,970 --> 00:08:13,672
Letter! What letter?

171
00:08:13,706 --> 00:08:15,207
I wrote it
and signed your name.

172
00:08:15,241 --> 00:08:16,975
[YELPS]

173
00:08:17,009 --> 00:08:18,977
Then she's reading it right now!

174
00:08:19,011 --> 00:08:20,011
Oh!

175
00:08:21,946 --> 00:08:24,648
Shh!

176
00:08:24,681 --> 00:08:25,782
[SIGHS]

177
00:08:25,816 --> 00:08:27,584
Sorry about that.

178
00:08:28,685 --> 00:08:29,886
So then

179
00:08:29,920 --> 00:08:32,021
the second penguin says,
"Why is that duck..."

180
00:08:32,054 --> 00:08:33,088
BRIANA:
<i>"Dear Briana,</i>

181
00:08:33,122 --> 00:08:35,157
<i>"ever since the first time</i>
<i>I met you,</i>

182
00:08:35,190 --> 00:08:38,993
<i>"I haven't been able</i>
<i>to take my eyes off of you.</i>

183
00:08:39,027 --> 00:08:40,628
<i>"I've been waiting</i>
<i>to get up the courage</i>

184
00:08:40,661 --> 00:08:42,896
<i>"to tell you how I feel.</i>

185
00:08:42,930 --> 00:08:45,165
<i>You are so beautiful..."</i>

186
00:08:45,198 --> 00:08:46,766
ASTRO:
<i>"And so very special.</i>

187
00:08:46,799 --> 00:08:49,636
<i>"I've never met</i>
<i>anyone like you.</i>

188
00:08:49,669 --> 00:08:53,172
<i>"And yet, I notice</i>
<i>you seem always to be alone.</i>

189
00:08:53,205 --> 00:08:56,074
<i>"I know what it means to feel</i>
<i>different and to be lonely,</i>

190
00:08:56,107 --> 00:08:58,143
<i>"to be so taken with a dream</i>

191
00:08:58,176 --> 00:09:01,211
<i>"that everything else</i>
<i>seems unreal.</i>

192
00:09:01,245 --> 00:09:04,181
<i>"To you, that dream</i>
<i>is space travel.</i>

193
00:09:04,214 --> 00:09:07,050
<i>To me, that dream is you."</i>

194
00:09:07,083 --> 00:09:08,752
BRIANA:
<i>"Signed, Anton."</i>

195
00:09:08,785 --> 00:09:10,119
[SIGHS]

196
00:09:10,153 --> 00:09:12,655
Anton.

197
00:09:12,688 --> 00:09:16,058
[DREAMILY]
Briana!

198
00:09:16,091 --> 00:09:18,159
[COMPUTER KEYS CLICKING]

199
00:09:20,027 --> 00:09:20,995
[PHONE RINGING]

200
00:09:22,629 --> 00:09:23,764
Hello?

201
00:09:23,797 --> 00:09:27,967
Oh, hi! Hold on.
I'll get him.

202
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:30,235
Telephone!
It's Briana.

203
00:09:30,269 --> 00:09:31,603
[GULPS]

204
00:09:31,636 --> 00:09:32,904
She's waiting!
Hurry up.

205
00:09:32,937 --> 00:09:34,873
[GULPS]

206
00:09:34,906 --> 00:09:35,907
I can't do it, Astro!

207
00:09:35,940 --> 00:09:38,676
You talk to her for me.
Huh?

208
00:09:38,709 --> 00:09:40,911
Pretend you're me.
Disguise your voice.

209
00:09:40,944 --> 00:09:42,212
Hmm.

210
00:09:44,114 --> 00:09:45,748
[CLEARS THROAT]

211
00:09:45,782 --> 00:09:48,918
[MIMICKING ANTON]
Hi, Briana. It's Anton.

212
00:09:48,951 --> 00:09:50,752
What's up?

213
00:09:50,786 --> 00:09:52,721
ANTON:
What!

214
00:09:52,754 --> 00:09:55,256
Briana wants to see me!

215
00:09:55,290 --> 00:09:56,524
Mm-hm.

216
00:09:56,557 --> 00:09:58,959
Oh, no! This is
like a nightmare.

217
00:09:58,993 --> 00:10:00,961
I thought it's
what you wanted.

218
00:10:00,995 --> 00:10:03,963
It is! But I didn't think
it would really happen.

219
00:10:03,997 --> 00:10:06,299
I don't know what to say.
I don't know what to do.

220
00:10:06,332 --> 00:10:07,533
What if I say
something stupid

221
00:10:07,566 --> 00:10:10,035
and she never
speaks to me again?

222
00:10:10,068 --> 00:10:12,637
What if I can't stop babbling
like I am now?

223
00:10:12,670 --> 00:10:14,038
Use this!
Huh?

224
00:10:14,071 --> 00:10:16,640
What's this? An earphone?

225
00:10:18,075 --> 00:10:19,610
ASTRO:
<i>Put it in your ear,</i>

226
00:10:19,643 --> 00:10:20,977
<i>and I'll tell you what to say.</i>

227
00:10:21,011 --> 00:10:25,047
Then, you just repeat my words.

228
00:10:28,717 --> 00:10:30,118
Ask her about the <i>Falcon.</i>

229
00:10:31,820 --> 00:10:34,989
Uh, Briana, I was
just wondering.

230
00:10:35,023 --> 00:10:37,591
Why are you working so hard
on the <i>Falcon</i> ?

231
00:10:37,625 --> 00:10:40,060
Because I want to go
beyond time.

232
00:10:40,093 --> 00:10:41,761
Beyond time?

233
00:10:41,794 --> 00:10:44,764
If-- If we surpass
the speed of light,

234
00:10:44,797 --> 00:10:47,833
I believe we'll travel
through time.

235
00:10:47,866 --> 00:10:50,601
But that's theoretically
impossible.

236
00:10:50,635 --> 00:10:52,070
Yes.

237
00:10:52,103 --> 00:10:54,805
That's what everyone
always tells me.

238
00:10:54,839 --> 00:10:56,040
I don't blame you at all

239
00:10:56,073 --> 00:10:57,774
for thinking I'm
a little bit foolish.

240
00:10:57,807 --> 00:10:59,776
No, no, I never--

241
00:10:59,809 --> 00:11:03,879
It's okay.
It's a normal reaction.

242
00:11:03,912 --> 00:11:06,181
Now tell her that what
you meant to say was,

243
00:11:06,214 --> 00:11:09,051
<i>"Impossible goals are</i>
<i>the only ones worth having."</i>

244
00:11:09,084 --> 00:11:12,653
Uh, Briana,
what I meant to say was...

245
00:11:12,687 --> 00:11:15,656
impossible goals are the only
ones worth having.

246
00:11:15,689 --> 00:11:17,691
And I just know
that you can do it.

247
00:11:17,724 --> 00:11:19,192
Anton, do you know

248
00:11:19,225 --> 00:11:22,361
you're the only one
who didn't make fun of my plans?

249
00:11:22,395 --> 00:11:24,063
That means so much to me.

250
00:11:24,096 --> 00:11:25,197
[GULPS]

251
00:11:25,230 --> 00:11:26,831
When I read your letter,

252
00:11:26,865 --> 00:11:28,733
I knew we were the same.

253
00:11:28,767 --> 00:11:30,768
And you understand me
like no one else.

254
00:11:30,801 --> 00:11:33,170
Briana, where will you
go beyond time?

255
00:11:33,203 --> 00:11:37,874
Briana, where will you
go beyond time?

256
00:11:37,907 --> 00:11:40,910
If I tell you, I know
you'll laugh at me.

257
00:11:40,943 --> 00:11:42,878
[SHOUTS]
I will never
laugh at you!

258
00:11:42,911 --> 00:11:45,046
Ugh!

259
00:11:45,080 --> 00:11:46,347
Astro!

260
00:11:46,381 --> 00:11:47,382
Anton?

261
00:11:47,415 --> 00:11:49,184
What's wrong?

262
00:11:49,217 --> 00:11:52,719
Uh, a dragonfly flew in my ear.

263
00:11:52,752 --> 00:11:54,188
I hate that.

264
00:11:54,221 --> 00:11:57,624
You asked me where
will I go beyond time.

265
00:11:57,657 --> 00:12:00,893
It's kind of
hard to explain. But...

266
00:12:00,926 --> 00:12:02,928
When I was a child,

267
00:12:02,961 --> 00:12:05,697
my father taught me
about the stars.

268
00:12:07,164 --> 00:12:10,767
He said the light
from the most distant stars

269
00:12:10,801 --> 00:12:13,837
takes millions of years
to reach the Earth.

270
00:12:13,870 --> 00:12:16,906
And I thought,
if I could become light,

271
00:12:16,939 --> 00:12:18,741
then I could be like the stars

272
00:12:18,774 --> 00:12:21,676
and travel to the farthest
corners of the cosmos.

273
00:12:21,710 --> 00:12:25,747
The ultimate limits of time.

274
00:12:31,852 --> 00:12:34,721
HEADMASTER:
And now it's time to name
this year's honors graduate,

275
00:12:34,754 --> 00:12:36,923
that student who has earned
the right to take part

276
00:12:36,956 --> 00:12:38,890
in a trans-galactic
space flight.

277
00:12:38,924 --> 00:12:41,393
Today, the Academy
is proud to announce

278
00:12:41,427 --> 00:12:43,061
the newest crew member
of the <i>Falcon Two,</i>

279
00:12:43,094 --> 00:12:45,430
Cadet Briana Turner!

280
00:12:45,463 --> 00:12:49,099
Cadet Turner,
please step forward.

281
00:12:49,133 --> 00:12:50,800
[ALL CHEERING]

282
00:12:53,102 --> 00:12:54,804
Isn't it great, Astro?

283
00:12:54,838 --> 00:12:56,872
And I've got a special
graduation surprise for her.

284
00:12:56,905 --> 00:12:58,073
What is it?

285
00:12:58,106 --> 00:12:59,742
You'll see.

286
00:12:59,775 --> 00:13:02,244
Astro, I really appreciate
all your help last night.

287
00:13:02,277 --> 00:13:04,779
I don't think I could
have done it on my own.

288
00:13:04,812 --> 00:13:07,214
Thanks to you, I feel
a lot more confident now.

289
00:13:07,248 --> 00:13:08,282
That's good.

290
00:13:08,315 --> 00:13:09,716
Maybe now you'll be able

291
00:13:09,750 --> 00:13:10,784
to talk to her
without fainting.

292
00:13:10,817 --> 00:13:11,918
Believe it!

293
00:13:11,952 --> 00:13:13,086
From now on,

294
00:13:13,119 --> 00:13:15,154
it's going to be
the real me all the way.

295
00:13:19,391 --> 00:13:21,860
[LIGHT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING]

296
00:13:23,794 --> 00:13:24,995
ASTRO:
Ah!

297
00:13:25,028 --> 00:13:26,997
Briana?

298
00:13:27,030 --> 00:13:29,866
[WHISPERING]
Follow me.

299
00:13:29,899 --> 00:13:32,034
I have a little
surprise for you.

300
00:13:32,068 --> 00:13:33,269
Hmm?

301
00:13:36,405 --> 00:13:39,240
Anton, we're not allowed
inside <i>Falcon Two.</i>

302
00:13:39,274 --> 00:13:41,842
It's cool.

303
00:13:41,876 --> 00:13:44,411
Nothing's off-limits
to a future astronaut.

304
00:13:50,850 --> 00:13:52,985
Congratulations!
Congratulations.

305
00:13:53,018 --> 00:13:55,487
Good luck, good luck.
You're number one.

306
00:13:55,521 --> 00:13:59,123
♪ Briana, Briana, Briana! ♪

307
00:13:59,157 --> 00:14:00,492
[GIGGLES]

308
00:14:00,525 --> 00:14:03,160
You really are
a mad scientist.

309
00:14:03,194 --> 00:14:05,429
Just made a few simple tweaks
to the ship's computer.

310
00:14:05,462 --> 00:14:06,897
[ROCKETS FIRE]

311
00:14:06,930 --> 00:14:08,398
[YELLS]

312
00:14:08,431 --> 00:14:09,232
COMPUTER:
<i>Initiate emergency</i>
<i>launch system.</i>

313
00:14:12,034 --> 00:14:14,469
Uh...is this part
of your surprise?

314
00:14:14,503 --> 00:14:16,405
No! I've got nothing
to do with this.

315
00:14:21,442 --> 00:14:23,944
ASTRO:
Anton!

316
00:14:23,977 --> 00:14:25,212
Briana!

317
00:14:28,948 --> 00:14:31,150
COMPUTER:
<i>Autopilot mode</i>
<i>has been activated.</i>

318
00:14:31,183 --> 00:14:32,418
<i>The ship will continue</i>
<i>in a straight course,</i>

319
00:14:32,451 --> 00:14:34,252
<i>awaiting instructions.</i>

320
00:14:34,285 --> 00:14:36,254
Autopilot! Oh, no!

321
00:14:36,287 --> 00:14:37,755
We gotta stop it!

322
00:14:42,026 --> 00:14:43,127
Did you alter
the ship's computer?

323
00:14:43,160 --> 00:14:44,294
A little.

324
00:14:44,328 --> 00:14:47,230
I was trying to add
dancing rosebuds,

325
00:14:47,263 --> 00:14:48,731
and I might have slightly
crashed the guidance system.

326
00:14:48,764 --> 00:14:52,234
COMPUTER:
<i>Impact with the moon</i>
<i>in 10 minutes and counting.</i>

327
00:14:52,267 --> 00:14:54,236
<i>Is this acceptable?</i>

328
00:14:54,269 --> 00:14:56,404
No, it's not acceptable!
Huh?

329
00:14:56,438 --> 00:14:58,873
COMPUTER:
<i>The white button signals yes.</i>

330
00:14:58,906 --> 00:15:00,974
<i>We will continue</i>
<i>on the current course.</i>

331
00:15:01,007 --> 00:15:03,343
ANTON:
Oh, this is not my day.

332
00:15:03,376 --> 00:15:05,078
Astro designed this program.

333
00:15:05,111 --> 00:15:07,813
He's the only one
who can fix it.

334
00:15:07,847 --> 00:15:09,414
Oh, man.

335
00:15:09,448 --> 00:15:12,251
I can't seem to do
anything right without Astro.

336
00:15:12,284 --> 00:15:15,019
I wish he was whispering
in my ear again right now.

337
00:15:15,053 --> 00:15:15,954
What do you mean?

338
00:15:17,955 --> 00:15:19,857
Look, Briana.

339
00:15:19,890 --> 00:15:22,092
All that stuff
I said last night...

340
00:15:22,125 --> 00:15:23,160
That wasn't me talking.

341
00:15:23,193 --> 00:15:25,194
That was Astro.

342
00:15:25,227 --> 00:15:28,864
He told me what to say.
And he wrote the letter too.

343
00:15:28,897 --> 00:15:30,532
I just wanted so much
for you to like me.

344
00:15:32,367 --> 00:15:33,801
So you lied to me?

345
00:15:33,834 --> 00:15:34,902
Uh...

346
00:15:34,935 --> 00:15:37,805
Um...

347
00:15:44,243 --> 00:15:46,179
Briana!

348
00:15:49,147 --> 00:15:51,183
Huh?

349
00:15:51,216 --> 00:15:52,317
Briana!
Astro!

350
00:15:52,350 --> 00:15:53,851
Anton!

351
00:15:53,885 --> 00:15:54,786
ANTON:
Astro, I'm sorry.

352
00:15:54,819 --> 00:15:57,054
I just meant to change
a few minor circuits.

353
00:15:57,088 --> 00:15:58,589
No. My design was flawed.

354
00:15:58,622 --> 00:16:00,556
It never occurred to me

355
00:16:00,590 --> 00:16:02,458
that the program
might be altered

356
00:16:02,492 --> 00:16:05,294
without addressing
the onboard drive circuit.

357
00:16:05,327 --> 00:16:09,898
I'm going to try to repair
the main drive computer.

358
00:16:10,231 --> 00:16:11,199
[BEEPS]

359
00:16:12,166 --> 00:16:12,934
[BEEPS]

360
00:16:17,437 --> 00:16:19,306
ANTON:
Astro.

361
00:16:19,339 --> 00:16:21,874
Can't you just push the ship
in a different direction?

362
00:16:21,908 --> 00:16:23,475
It won't work.

363
00:16:23,509 --> 00:16:24,910
The automatic course correction

364
00:16:24,943 --> 00:16:27,546
will just bring it
right back on track.

365
00:16:34,451 --> 00:16:36,486
No response.
I can't stop it.

366
00:16:36,520 --> 00:16:37,954
The escape pod!
No.

367
00:16:37,987 --> 00:16:39,422
The escape pods
and the spacesuits

368
00:16:39,455 --> 00:16:41,490
haven't been
installed yet.

369
00:16:41,524 --> 00:16:43,959
COMPUTER:
<i>Impact with the moon,</i>
<i>three minutes and counting.</i>

370
00:16:43,992 --> 00:16:46,261
Can't you just shut
the computer system down?

371
00:16:46,294 --> 00:16:48,029
No good.

372
00:16:48,062 --> 00:16:51,265
I designed the central processor
to hand over control

373
00:16:51,298 --> 00:16:54,034
to the emergency backup system
in case of a shutdown.

374
00:16:54,067 --> 00:16:57,037
Looks like I outsmarted myself
at every turn.

375
00:16:57,070 --> 00:17:00,072
The perfect system.

376
00:17:00,105 --> 00:17:03,308
Oh, how could I have done
such a foolish thing!

377
00:17:03,342 --> 00:17:05,944
You can't give up.
There must be some way.

378
00:17:08,346 --> 00:17:11,415
This system is a product
of Astro's brain, right?

379
00:17:11,449 --> 00:17:12,550
So--

380
00:17:12,583 --> 00:17:15,285
Astro must somehow defeat Astro.

381
00:17:15,318 --> 00:17:16,953
But how?

382
00:17:16,986 --> 00:17:20,256
Ah! Astro! You become
the backup system.

383
00:17:20,289 --> 00:17:21,657
That's it!
Great idea.

384
00:17:21,690 --> 00:17:23,325
If you can connect

385
00:17:23,359 --> 00:17:25,493
Astro's central processor
with the ship's--

386
00:17:25,526 --> 00:17:27,062
Then the ship's
guidance system

387
00:17:27,095 --> 00:17:29,196
will become part of
Astro's electronic brain.

388
00:17:29,229 --> 00:17:31,932
You ready, Astro?
Okay.

389
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:36,135
[GASPS]

390
00:17:36,169 --> 00:17:37,170
Whoa!

391
00:17:37,203 --> 00:17:40,072
[YELLING]

392
00:17:41,073 --> 00:17:44,509
[♪]

393
00:17:44,542 --> 00:17:46,010
Oh!

394
00:17:52,549 --> 00:17:54,217
FALCON TWO:
<i>I am</i> Falcon Two.

395
00:17:54,250 --> 00:17:55,385
<i>Identify yourself.</i>

396
00:17:55,418 --> 00:17:58,253
I am--

397
00:17:58,287 --> 00:17:59,321
[GROANS]

398
00:17:59,354 --> 00:18:01,423
Astro's absorbing
masses of data.

399
00:18:01,456 --> 00:18:03,525
I'm not sure
he can take it.

400
00:18:03,558 --> 00:18:05,359
COMPUTER:
<i>Impact with the moon,</i>
<i>30 seconds and counting.</i>

401
00:18:05,393 --> 00:18:08,028
[GROANING]

402
00:18:11,131 --> 00:18:13,400
[WEAKLY]
Briana.
Yes?

403
00:18:13,433 --> 00:18:15,301
Help me. Please help me.

404
00:18:15,334 --> 00:18:17,269
Oh.

405
00:18:23,108 --> 00:18:27,311
<i>Astro, you can do it.</i>

406
00:18:27,344 --> 00:18:29,446
[GASPS]

407
00:18:29,479 --> 00:18:31,448
I am--

408
00:18:31,481 --> 00:18:35,284
I...am...Astro!

409
00:18:35,318 --> 00:18:38,520
COMPUTER:
<i>Ten seconds. Nine...</i>

410
00:18:38,553 --> 00:18:41,223
FALCON TWO:
<i>You are...same.</i>

411
00:18:41,256 --> 00:18:44,926
We are...Astro!

412
00:18:46,493 --> 00:18:48,261
We did it!

413
00:18:48,294 --> 00:18:49,963
<i>Falcon</i> and Astro
are synchronized!

414
00:18:49,996 --> 00:18:53,266
COMPUTER:
<i>Zero. Impact.</i>

415
00:19:01,739 --> 00:19:04,642
Astro, your feelings
for Briana

416
00:19:04,675 --> 00:19:06,744
gave you the strength
to overpower <i>Falcon Two.</i>

417
00:19:06,777 --> 00:19:11,447
Now, that is
major <i>kokoro!</i>

418
00:19:20,521 --> 00:19:22,523
Have a great
flight, Briana.

419
00:19:22,557 --> 00:19:23,991
Congratulations.

420
00:19:24,024 --> 00:19:25,759
They're lovely. Thank you.

421
00:19:25,792 --> 00:19:28,394
You know, you two really
shouldn't have deceived me.

422
00:19:28,427 --> 00:19:29,662
Uh--
Uh--

423
00:19:29,695 --> 00:19:30,763
We're sorry.
Sorry.

424
00:19:30,796 --> 00:19:33,098
You didn't need
to put on an act for me.

425
00:19:33,131 --> 00:19:36,134
Anton, I liked you for yourself
the minute I met you.

426
00:19:36,168 --> 00:19:39,403
And, Astro, you have more
courage than any human I know.

427
00:19:39,437 --> 00:19:41,638
I guess I should have
had the courage

428
00:19:41,672 --> 00:19:43,374
to just be honest with you.

429
00:19:43,407 --> 00:19:45,075
Now, when I get back,

430
00:19:45,108 --> 00:19:48,011
I want you both to promise me
there'll be no more games.

431
00:19:48,044 --> 00:19:49,712
Deal?
Deal.

432
00:19:49,745 --> 00:19:52,047
[BOTH LAUGH]

433
00:19:52,081 --> 00:19:54,516
Astro, you too.

434
00:19:56,651 --> 00:19:59,287
Whoa!

435
00:20:02,556 --> 00:20:04,557
Time for me to go.

436
00:20:06,158 --> 00:20:07,994
Beyond time, Briana!

437
00:20:09,195 --> 00:20:11,163
ALL:
Yeah! Briana!

438
00:20:11,197 --> 00:20:13,164
[ALL CHEERING]

439
00:20:17,268 --> 00:20:20,104
Well, there she goes,
my one and only.

440
00:20:20,137 --> 00:20:21,684
Oh, we'll
see her again.

441
00:20:22,784 --> 00:20:24,450
Yeah.

442
00:20:24,484 --> 00:20:26,784
And when we do, may the best
man or boy or robot win.

443
00:20:26,817 --> 00:20:29,684
Right.

444
00:20:29,717 --> 00:20:31,484
[ASTRO AND ANTON LAUGHING]

445
00:20:39,550 --> 00:20:41,484
[♪]

